    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i get the twin/dice thing but it still feels a bit vague. can u explain the 'spooky action at a distance' part more? like why don't scientists just call it a hidden variable or something? why is the connection so weirdly instant?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Of course, let's dive deeper into that spooky action at a distance! Imagine you have two magical, invisible strings connecting two enchanted dice. When you roll one die, the other die instantly shows the same number, even if it's on the other side of the world. This is what scientists call \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seems to happen faster than the speed of light, which is weird and mysterious.\n\nNow, some scientists thought there might be a hidden variable, like a secret spell or a magical force, that explains this instant connection. But after many experiments, they found that there isn't any hidden variable. The connection between entangled particles is so weirdly instant that it can't be explained by any known forces or hidden variables. It's like the dice are connected by a magical force that makes them instantly share their numbers, no matter how far apart they are.\n\nThis spooky action at a distance is one of the strangest and most fascinating things in quantum physics. It's like having a pair of enchanted dice that always show the same number, no matter how far apart they are rolled. And that's why scientists call it \"spooky\" – because it's so weird and mysterious!",
